[Further information on the etiology of this outbreak of encephalitis is
awaited. It is likely that Japanese encephalitis virus is the agent
responsible for this outbreak. Japanese Encephalitis virus-induced disease
was first identified in 1978 in the Ganges plain, in the region of the
Nepalese Terai, along the border between Nepal and India. Since then annual
epidemics of varying sizes have been recorded in Nepal and adjacent regions
of India during the rainy season. The largest number of reported cases was
2953 in 1997. In 1999 the epidemic began about two weeks early (in early
July) due probably to early onset of to the monsoon rains. By the end of
August there had been more that 1100 cases and over 170 deaths had been
reported in the Terai region of Nepal. In past years there have been
sporadic localized immunization campaigns, using the killed Biken mouse
brain vaccine, carried out by international charitable organizations, but
the follow-up has been erratic. - Mod.CP
